# Mach Terminal — Agent Operating Rules

## 1. ALWAYS consult the Master Runbook FIRST

A federated runbook lives in `.cursor/runbook/`. Before planning or editing anything,
read `.cursor/runbook/00_INDEX.md`, then load ONLY the file(s) relevant to your task
(do not read all of them — that wastes context):

| If your task involves... | Read |
| --- | --- |
| Orientation / "what is this project" / North Star | `00_INDEX.md` |
| Tech stack, data flow, IPC, system patterns, external APIs | `01_ARCHITECTURE.md` |
| Where code lives, module responsibilities, routing, config, state location | `02_COMPONENTS_AND_FILES.md` |
| Coding conventions, error handling, state rules, testing/CI, gotchas | `03_RULES_AND_STANDARDS.md` |
| What works/broken, backlog, next steps, pre-commit verification | `04_CURRENT_STATE.md` |

Treat the runbook as authoritative for *how this repo is built and why*. When the runbook
conflicts with an assumption, the runbook wins; if the runbook conflicts with the actual
code, the code wins — and you must fix the runbook (see §3).

## 2. Respect the non-negotiables (full detail in `03_RULES_AND_STANDARDS.md`)

- Core terminal must work with AI/providers disabled. AI is optional, never a dependency.
- All backend access goes through the `src/core/terminal.ts` bridge. Keep `models.rs`
  (Rust DTOs) and `terminal.ts` (TS types) in lockstep.
- Cross-boundary changes require the full checklist: module → `#[tauri::command]` →
  `generate_handler![]` registry → `models.rs` DTO → `terminal.ts` wrapper → consumer → tests.
- Backend commands return `Result<_, String>` with user-facing messages; frontend wraps every
  invoke in try/catch. Fail gracefully, recover from corruption, never silently reset.
- Prefer pure helpers in `src/core/*` / `src/state/*` with colocated tests over logic in React.
- Prune every per-session `Record<sessionId,...>` when sessions die.

## 3. ALWAYS update the Runbook BEFORE you commit

The runbook is the durable handoff for the next agent/developer. Keeping it current is part of
"done", not an afterthought.

Before creating any git commit, in the SAME change:
1. Update the runbook file(s) affected by your work:
   - new/changed architecture, data flow, or external dep → `01_ARCHITECTURE.md`
   - new/moved/renamed modules or responsibilities → `02_COMPONENTS_AND_FILES.md`
   - new conventions, gotchas, or tech debt → `03_RULES_AND_STANDARDS.md`
   - anything shipped/broken/unblocked or a changed next step → `04_CURRENT_STATE.md`
   - changed scope/summary/North Star → `00_INDEX.md`
2. Keep entries concise, bullet-driven, and grounded in the actual code you changed.
3. If nothing in the runbook is affected, state that explicitly in your summary — do not pad it.
4. Mirror material changes into the upstream truth sources where appropriate
   (`docs/continuation-handoff.md`, `CHANGELOG.md`) per existing repo practice.

## 4. Verify before committing

Run the gate from `04_CURRENT_STATE.md`:
`npm run test:types && npm run test:ux && npm run test:ux:smoke && cargo test --manifest-path src-tauri/Cargo.toml`
(plus `npm run test:invoke:smoke && npm run test:invoke:strict` if touching invoke transport).

## 5. Commit message format

`[TICKET] :gitmoji: type(scope): summary` — gitmoji per https://gitmoji.dev, optional bullet
body as `* :gitmoji: ...`, NO commit trailers (no Co-authored-by / Signed-off-by). Omit the
`[TICKET]` prefix if none is provided.

> Note: `.cursor/` is currently in `.gitignore`. If the runbook should be version-controlled and
> shared (so this update-before-commit rule actually propagates), add `!.cursor/runbook/` to
> `.gitignore`. `.cursorrules` itself is tracked.
